[{"type":"text/html","content":"<p>Our next stop on our American Futures partnership with The Atlantic didn’t take us too far from Marketplace headquarters in downtown Los Angeles. </p>"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p><em>Follow Marketplace&apos;s Kai Ryssdal and the Atlantic&apos;s James Fallows as they tour Redlands Foothills Grove packing plant -- the last orange packing house in town.</em></p>"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p><iframe frameborder="0" src="//player.vimeo.com/video/82409902"></iframe></p>"},{"content":"<p><span>Redlands, Calif., is about an hour east of L.A. and also happens to be where James Fallows grew up. </span></p>","type":"text/html"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p>Redlands was at one point the navel orange growing capital of the world. Today, just a small fraction of the old groves remain – they’ve been plowed up and built over.</p>"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p><em><img alt="" src="http://www.marketplace.org/sites/default/files/styles/primary-image-610x340/public/null/_MG_0925.JPG?itok=b4xqkPpT" /></em></p>"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p>&quot;The story people tell themselves here is how lucky they are to have all the fruits of the generation of people who&apos;ve planted groves, who&apos;ve built parks and so it&apos;s up to them both to be aware of that and to make the investment for the next generation so they&apos;ve got a kind of local patriotism we&apos;ve found in a lot of other very different cities,&quot; says Fallows about his hometown. </p>"},{"content":"<p>Nowadays, the groves may be gone but that doesn’t mean the city can’t use oranges to help build its future. A future that can be found, funnily enough, in beer from the local brewery, <a href="http://www.hangar24brewery.com/" target="_blank">Hangar 24</a>. </p>","type":"text/html"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p>Founded by Ben Cook about five years ago, Hangar 24 is one of the fastest-growing craft breweries in the country and it’s widely known for its orange wheat beer. Cook says about 70 percent of their production is of the citrus-infused variety and most of the oranges he uses are grown about five miles from the brewery. </p>"},{"content":"<p>In fact, Hangar 24 is one of Bob Knight’s biggest customers. Knight is a four<span>th</span>-generation orange farmer in Redlands.</p>","type":"text/html"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p>One of his groves borders the south side of town – 23 acres of densely-packed trees weighed down with fruit.      </p>"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p>Knight runs the family business but he does things differently than the way his father and grandfather did. Instead of selling into the global market – sending his oranges to the local Sunkist packing house to be boxed and sold around the world, Knight keeps his oranges close to home.</p>"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p>Besides Hangar 24, he also sells to school districts around Southern California. </p>"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p><span><img alt="" src="http://www.marketplace.org/sites/default/files/styles/primary-image-610x340/public/null/IMG_4856.JPG?itok=vNS3osq7" /></span></p>"},{"content":"<p>And while Knight recognizes the city doesn’t have the recognition in the orange business it used to, he’s not bothered.</p>","type":"text/html"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p>&quot;The orange industry, from the city of Redlands, from an economic or financial point of view is minute,&quot; Knight says. &quot;But from a heart-share point of view, it’s huge.&quot;</p>"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p>The city of Redlands even owns orange groves – paid for by a voter-approved measure in the 1980s that was intended to help preserve about 200 acres of orange trees.</p>"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p>A vestige of the city’s booming citrus industry does remain – one last Sunkist packing house right in the heart of the city. It’s called Redlands Foothills Grove -- run by a man named Manuel Martinez.</p>"},{"content":"<p><span><img alt="" src="http://www.marketplace.org/sites/default/files/styles/primary-image-610x340/public/null/asfasdf.jpg?itok=g6-34YbM" /></span></p>","type":"text/html"},{"content":"<p><span><em>A photo of the last remaining packing house, Redlands Foothill Groves</em></span></p>","type":"text/html"},{"content":"<p>Martinez says the orange business isn’t getting any easier. There aren’t enough local growers to keep the plant going so he’s had to bring oranges in from other regions – Bakersfield and Arizona – to survive. But this packing plant is how Redlands keeps a tiny finger in the global orange market. It boxes up oranges that end in grocery stores across the United States, in Hong Kong and even Japan.</p>","type":"text/html"},{"content":"<p><em><img alt="" src="http://www.marketplace.org/sites/default/files/styles/primary-image-610x340/public/null/IMG_4863.JPG?itok=yyrSY_6S" /></em></p>","type":"text/html"},{"content":"<p>The orange industry has changed but oranges are right at the heart of what Redlands is using to get people to live here. They brand the place with oranges – from the names of streets to street signs, murals around downtown and the city seal.</p>","type":"text/html"},{"content":"<p>And while the city might not have a reputation that spans from coast to coast, the people that live in Redlands remain devoted to their heritage. </p>","type":"text/html"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p><em><img alt="" src="http://www.marketplace.org/sites/default/files/styles/primary-image-610x340/public/null/IMG_4881.JPG?itok=Xki7JOHB" /></em></p>"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p><em>How much do you know about this small town of Redlands? <a href="http://www.marketplace.org/topics/economy/american-futures/redlands-calif-quiz-how-well-do-you-know-city-famous-its-oranges" target="_blank">Take our quiz</a>!</em></p>"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<div class="pd-embed" id="pd_1387482792"></div>"},{"content":"<script type="text/javascript">
